{"title_page": "Andr\u00e9 Canonne", "text_new": "{{multiple issues|\n{{no footnotes|date=February 2017}}\n{{orphan|date=December 2013}}\n{{Expand French|Andr\u00e9 Canonne|date=December 2013}}\n}}\n'''Andr\u00e9 Canonne''' (2 December 1937 \u2013 13 August 1990) was a Belgian writer and librarian.\n\n== Early life ==\nAndr\u00e9 Canonne was born in the town of [[Wasmes]] in Belgium.\n\n== Career ==\nAndr\u00e9 Canonne held numerous jobs as a librarian and archivist. He provided assistance to the French department of public libraries.\n\nHe was the chief librarian of the central library of [[Hainaut (province)|Hainaut]].\n\nHe wrote a number of books on librarianship and management of books and information.\n\nHe was the guardian and promoter of [[Paul Otlet]]'s [[Mundaneum]] institution.\n\n== Bibliography ==\n\n* ''Manuel \u00e9l\u00e9mentaire de catalographie'' (Ed. du CLPCF, 1986, {{ISBN|2-87130-008-9}})\n* ''Dis, donne moi une histoire : r\u00e9pertoire th\u00e9matique d'albums de fictions pour enfants'' (Ed. du CLPCF, 1989 ; \n* ''Vocabulaire \u00e9l\u00e9mentaire des classifications'' (Ed. CEFAL, 1993, {{ISBN|2-87130-029-1}})\n* ''Trait\u00e9 de documentation : le livre sur le livre, th\u00e9orie et pratique'' (Ed. du CLPCF, 1989 ; r\u00e9imp. de l'\u00e9d. de 1934 ; Pr\u00e9face de [[Robert Estivals]], Avant-propos d'Andr\u00e9 Canonne. {{ISBN|2-87130-015-1}})\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* http://www.litteraturedejeunesse.cfwb.be/index.php\n* http://bbf.enssib.fr/consulter/bbf-1995-05-0100-005\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Canonne, Andre}}\n[[Category:1937 births]]\n[[Category:1990 deaths]]\n[[Category:Belgian non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Belgian male writers]]\n[[Category:Belgian librarians]]\n[[Category:People from Hainaut (province)]]\n\n\n{{Belgium-writer-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{multiple issues|\n{{inline|date=February 2017}}\n{{orphan|date=December 2013}}\n{{Expand French|Andr\u00e9 Canonne|date=December 2013}}\n}}\n'''Andr\u00e9 Canonne''' (2 December 1937 \u2013 13 August 1990) was a Belgian writer and librarian.\n\n== Early life ==\nAndr\u00e9 Canonne was born in the town of [[Wasmes]] in Belgium.\n\n== Career ==\nAndr\u00e9 Canonne held numerous jobs as a librarian and archivist. He provided assistance to the French department of public libraries.\n\nHe was the chief librarian of the central library of [[Hainaut (province)|Hainaut]].\n\nHe wrote a number of books on librarianship and management of books and information.\n\nHe was the guardian and promoter of [[Paul Otlet]]'s [[Mundaneum]] institution.\n\n== Bibliography ==\n\n* ''Manuel \u00e9l\u00e9mentaire de catalographie'' (Ed. du CLPCF, 1986, {{ISBN|2-87130-008-9}})\n* ''Dis, donne moi une histoire : r\u00e9pertoire th\u00e9matique d'albums de fictions pour enfants'' (Ed. du CLPCF, 1989 ; \n* ''Vocabulaire \u00e9l\u00e9mentaire des classifications'' (Ed. CEFAL, 1993, {{ISBN|2-87130-029-1}})\n* ''Trait\u00e9 de documentation : le livre sur le livre, th\u00e9orie et pratique'' (Ed. du CLPCF, 1989 ; r\u00e9imp. de l'\u00e9d. de 1934 ; Pr\u00e9face de [[Robert Estivals]], Avant-propos d'Andr\u00e9 Canonne. {{ISBN|2-87130-015-1}})\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* http://www.litteraturedejeunesse.cfwb.be/index.php\n* http://bbf.enssib.fr/consulter/bbf-1995-05-0100-005\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Canonne, Andre}}\n[[Category:1937 births]]\n[[Category:1990 deaths]]\n[[Category:Belgian non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Belgian male writers]]\n[[Category:Belgian librarians]]\n[[Category:People from Hainaut (province)]]\n\n\n{{Belgium-writer-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Andr%C3%A9_Canonne"}
{"title_page": "Margaret Amosu", "text_new": "'''Margaret Amosu''' (died 2005) was a British-Nigerian librarian. She was librarian at the [[University of Ibadan]] from 1963 to 1977.<ref name=GuardianObit>Vaughan Melzer and Akwe Amosu, [https://www.theguardian.com/news/2005/sep/30/obituaries.mainsection Margaret Amosu], ''[[The Guardian]]'', 30 September 2005.</ref>\n\n==Life==\nMargaret Amosu was born 3 August 1920 in Ilford near London. She was educated at [[Harrow Weald]] County School, where she was taught by James Britten, Nancy Martin and [[Harold Rosen (educationalist)|Harold Rosen]]. In 1938 she joined the [[Land Army]] and then worked as a riveter in an aircraft factory. A Communist, trade unionist and internationalist, as shop steward, she ensured women workers received the full rate for their factory jobs.<ref name=GuardianObit/>\n\nIn 1944 she fell in love with Arthur Melzer, a [[Czechoslovak]] communist. In 1945 he discovered that his family had survived German occupation, and returned to them, days before the birth of his daughter Vaughan. Struggling against prejudice as an unmarried mother, Margaret became librarian at the [[Chester Beatty Cancer Research Institute]] in 1948. In 1957 she married the Nigerian anti-colonial activist [[Nunasu Amosu]], who was studying in Britain. Their daughter was born in 1960, and in 1963 she moved to [[Ibadan]] and became librarian at the [[University of Ibadan]]. There she published a bibliography of African creative writing, helped develop an Africa-centred curriculum, and oversaw the building of a new library as medical librarian of the country's main teaching hospital.<ref name=GuardianObit/>\n\nIn 1977 she returned to England, becoming librarian of [[Phaidon Press]] in [[Oxford]].<ref name=GuardianObit/>\n\n==Works==\n* ''A preliminary bibliography of creative African writing in the European languages'', 1960\n* ''Nigerian theses; a list of theses on Nigerian subjects and of theses by Nigerians'', 1965\n* (ed. with O. Soyinka and E. O. Osuniana) ''25 years of medical research, 1948-1973 : a list of the papers published by past and present members of the Faculty of Medicine of the University of Ibadan from its foundation to November 1973'', 1973\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.iwm.org.uk/collections/item/object/80016170 Margaret Amosu: Oral History interview], [[Imperial War Museum]], 1996.\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Amosu, Margaret}}\n[[Category:1921 births]]\n[[Category:Year of birth uncertain]]\n[[Category:2005 deaths]]\n[[Category:British librarians]]\n[[Category:British bibliographers]]\n[[Category:Nigerian librarians]]\n[[Category:British communists]]\n[[Category:British trade unionists]]\n[[Category:University of Ibadan people]]\n", "text_old": "'''Margaret Amosu''' (died 2005) was a British-Nigerian librarian. She was librarian at the [[University of Ibadan]] from 1963 to 1977.<ref name=GuardianObit>Vaughan Melzer and Akwe Amosu, [https://www.theguardian.com/news/2005/sep/30/obituaries.mainsection Margaret Amosu], ''[[The Guardian]]'', 30 September 2005.</ref>\n\n==Life==\nMargaret was educated at [[Harrow Weald]] County School, where she was taught by James Britten, Nancy Martin and [[Harold Rosen (educationalist)|Harold Rosen]]. In 1938 she joined the [[Land Army]] and then worked as a riveter in an aircraft factory. A Communist, trade unionist and internationalist, as shop steward, she ensured women workers received the full rate for their factory jobs.<ref name=GuardianObit/>\n\nIn 1944 she fell in love with Arthur Melzer, a [[Czechoslovak]] communist. In 1945 he discovered that his family had survived German occupation, and returned to them, days before the birth of his daughter Vaughan. Struggling against prejudice as an unmarried mother, Margaret became librarian at the [[Chester Beatty Cancer Research Institute]] in 1948. In 1957 she married the Nigerian anti-colonial activist [[Nunasu Amosu]], who was studying in Britain. Their daughter was born in 1960, and in 1963 she moved to [[Ibadan]] and became librarian at the [[University of Ibadan]]. There she published a bibliography of African creative writing, helped develop an Africa-centred curriculum, and oversaw the building of a new library as medical librarian of the country's main teaching hospital.<ref name=GuardianObit/>\n\nIn 1977 she returned to England, becoming librarian of [[Phaidon Press]] in [[Oxford]].<ref name=GuardianObit/>\n\n==Works==\n* ''A preliminary bibliography of creative African writing in the European languages'', 1960\n* ''Nigerian theses; a list of theses on Nigerian subjects and of theses by Nigerians'', 1965\n* (ed. with O. Soyinka and E. O. Osuniana) ''25 years of medical research, 1948-1973 : a list of the papers published by past and present members of the Faculty of Medicine of the University of Ibadan from its foundation to November 1973'', 1973\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.iwm.org.uk/collections/item/object/80016170 Margaret Amosu: Oral History interview], [[Imperial War Museum]], 1996.\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Amosu, Margaret}}\n[[Category:1921 births]]\n[[Category:Year of birth uncertain]]\n[[Category:2005 deaths]]\n[[Category:British librarians]]\n[[Category:British bibliographers]]\n[[Category:Nigerian librarians]]\n[[Category:British communists]]\n[[Category:British trade unionists]]\n[[Category:University of Ibadan people]]\n", "name_user": "Akwea", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLife:inserted birth date (1920) and location.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Margaret_Amosu"}
{"title_page": "Russia at the 2016 Summer Olympics", "text_new": "{{lead rewrite|date=December 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{infobox country at games\n| NOC = RUS\n| NOCname = [[Russian Olympic Committee]]\n| games = Summer Olympics\n| year = 2016\n| flagcaption = \n| oldcode = \n| website = {{url|www.olympic.ru }}&nbsp;{{in lang|ru}}\n| location = [[Rio de Janeiro]]\n| competitors = 282\n| sports = 26\n| flagbearer = [[Sergey Tetyukhin]] (opening)<ref>{{cite news|url=http://tass.ru/en/sport/891174|title=Volleyball star Tetyukhin named Russia\u2019s Olympic flag bearer|publisher=[[Russian News Agency TASS]]|date=28 July 2016|accessdate=29 July 2016}}</ref><br />[[Natalia Ishchenko]] and [[Svetlana Romashina]] (closing)\n| rank = 4\n| gold = 19\n| silver = 17\n| bronze = 20\n| appearances = auto\n| app_begin_year = 1996\n| app_end_year = \n| summerappearances = \n| winterappearances = \n| seealso = {{flagIOC|RU1}} (1900\u20131912)<br/>{{flagIOC|URS}} (1952\u20131988)<br/>{{flagIOC|EUN}} (1992)<br />{{flagIOC|OAR|2018 Winter}} (''2018'')\n}}\n\nThe '''[[Russian Federation]]''' competed at the [[2016 Summer Olympics]] in [[Rio de Janeiro]], Brazil, from 5 to 21 August 2016. This was [[Russia]]'s sixth consecutive appearance at the Summer Olympics as an independent nation.\n\nOn 18 July 2016, an independent investigation commissioned by [[World Anti-Doping Agency]] concluded that it was shown \"beyond a reasonable doubt\" that the [[RUSADA]], the [[Ministry of Sport (Russia)|Ministry of Sport]], the [[Federal Security Service]] (FSB) and the Centre of Sports Preparation of the National Teams of Russia had \"operated for the protection of doped Russian athletes\" within a \"state-directed failsafe system\" using \"the disappearing positive [test] methodology.\" According to the [[McLaren Report]], the Disappearing Positive Methodology operated from \"at least late 2011 to August 2015.\" It was used on 643 positive samples, a number that the authors consider \"only a minimum\" due to limited access to Russian records. Based on these findings the [[International Olympic Committee]] called for an emergency meeting to consider banning Russia from the Summer Olympics.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/07/19/sports/report-confirms-state-sponsored-doping-by-russia-at-olympics.html|title=Russia May Face Olympics Ban as Doping Scheme Is Confirmed|last=Ruiz|first=Rebecca|date=18 July 2016|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|issn=0362-4331|accessdate=26 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 July, the IOC rejected WADA's recommendation to ban Russia from the Summer Olympics and announced that a decision would be made by each sport federation. With each positive decision having to be approved by a CAS arbitrator. On 7 August 2016, the IOC cleared 278 athletes, while 111 were removed because of the scandal.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/othersports/article-3728841/IOC-confirm-278-Russian-athletes-eligible-compete-Rio-Olympics.html|title=IOC confirm 278 Russian athletes are eligible to compete at Rio|date=9 July 2016|publisher=[[Daily Mail]]|accessdate=9 August 2016}}</ref><ref name=\":14\">{{Cite web|url=http://en.europeonline-magazine.eu/backgroundrussian-athletes-participating-in-rio-olympic-game-by-federation_475489.html |title=Russian athletes participating in Rio Olympic Game by federation |date=9 August 2016 |publisher=Europe Online Magazine |accessdate=9 August 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160809043949/http://en.europeonline-magazine.eu/backgroundrussian-athletes-participating-in-rio-olympic-game-by-federation_475489.html |archivedate= 9 August 2016 }}</ref>\n\nOn 7 August 2016, the [[International Paralympic Committee]] announced that it had voted unanimously to ban the entire Russian Paralympic team from competing at the 2016 Summer Paralympics, in the wake of a larger scandal that exposed the participation of Russian Olympic and Paralympic athletes in a [[Doping in Russia|state-sponsored doping program]]. \n\nOn 8 December 2016, silver medalist [[Misha Aloyan]] was found to have committed an anti-doping rule violation after testing positive for Tuaminoheptane, a specified stimulant, prohibited in-competition under S6 on the WADA Prohibited List, during an in-competition doping control on 21 August 2016. The results obtained by the athlete at the Rio 2016 Olympic Games were disqualified.<ref name=\"tas-cas.org\">[http://www.tas-cas.org/fileadmin/user_upload/Media_Release_AD_16-10_and_16_11.pdf  ANTI-DOPING DIVISION OF THE COURT OF ARBITRATION FOR SPORT ISSUES DECISIONS IN THE CASE OF MISHA ALOIAN]</ref>\n\nOn 9 December 2016, Canadian lawyer [[Richard McLaren (academic)|Richard McLaren]] published the second part of his [[McLaren Report|independent report]]. The investigation claimed that from 2011 to 2015, more than 1,000 Russian competitors in various sports (including summer, winter, and Paralympic sports) were involved in a cover-up.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.wada-ama.org/en/resources/doping-control-process/mclaren-independent-investigation-report-part-ii|title=MCLAREN INDEPENDENT INVESTIGATION REPORT \u2013 PART II|work=wada-ama.org|date= 9 December 2016}}</ref><ref name=NYT161209>{{cite news |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2016/12/09/sports/russia-doping-mclaren-report.html |title=Russia\u2019s Doping Program Laid Bare by Extensive Evidence in Report |work= The New York Times |first= Rebecca R. |last= Ruiz |date= 9 December 2016 }}</ref><ref name=Guardian161209>{{cite news |url= https://www.theguardian.com/sport/live/2016/dec/09/mclaren-report-into-doping-in-sport-part-two-live |title= McLaren report: more than 1,000 Russian athletes involved in doping conspiracy |work= The Guardian |first= Lawrence |last= Ostlere |date= 9 December 2016 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180801221511/https://www.tas-cas.org/fileadmin/user_upload/Award__5379__internet.pdf|title=Wayback Machine|date=1 August 2018|website=web.archive.org|access-date=22 June 2019}}</ref> Emails indicate that athletes who tested positive for banned substances included five blind powerlifters, who may have been given drugs without their knowledge, and a fifteen-year-old.<ref name=AP161213>{{cite news |url= https://apnews.com/8be9cb7fcb5b4d65b1031597bb9f9e5e/Emails-show-how-Russian-officials-covered-up-mass-doping |title= Emails show how Russian officials covered up mass doping |first= James |last= Ellingworth |work= [[Associated Press]] |date= 13 December 2016 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20161214061329/https://apnews.com/8be9cb7fcb5b4d65b1031597bb9f9e5e/Emails-show-how-Russian-officials-covered-up-mass-doping |archivedate= 14 December 2016 |url-status= live }}</ref>\n\n==Medalists {{ref label|a|a|Medal Changes}} ==\n{{main article|2016 Summer Olympics medal table}}\n{{col-begin}}\n| width=78% align=left valign=top |\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"  style=\"font-size:95%\"\n|-\n! Medal\n! Name\n! Sport\n! Event\n! Date\n|-\n| {{gold medal}} || {{sortname|Beslan|Mudranov}} || [[Judo at the 2016 Summer Olympics|Judo]] || [[Judo at the 2016 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's 60 kg|Men's 60 kg]] || {{dts|6 August}}\n|-\n|  {{gold medal}} || {{sortname|Yana|Egorian}} || [[Fencing at the 2016 Summer Olympics|Fencing]] || [[Fencing at the 2016 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's sabre|Women's sabre]] || {{dts|8 August}}\n|-\n| {{gold medal}} || {{sortname|Khasan|Khalmurzaev}} || [[Judo at the 2016 Summer Olympics|Judo]] || [[Judo at the 2016 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's 81 kg|Men's 81 kg]] || {{dts|9 August}}\n|-\n|  {{gold medal}} || {{sortname|Inna|Deriglazova}} || [[Fencing at the 2016 Summer Olympics|Fencing]] || [[Fencing at the 2016 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's foil|Women's foil]] || {{dts|10 August}}\n|-\n| {{gold medal}} || {{sortname|Artur|Akhmatkhuzin}}<br/>[[Aleksey Cheremisinov]]<br/>[[Timur Safin]] || [[Fencing at the 2016 Summer Olympics|Fencing]] || [[Fencing at t