2013 Men's light heavyweight|Light heavyweight]]\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[Albert Ramirez|Ramirez]]|VEN|2016 Summer}}<br />'''L''' 1\u20132\n|colspan=5|Did not advance\n|-align=center\n|align=left|'''[[Evgeny Tishchenko]]'''\n|align=left|[[Boxing at the 2016 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's heavyweight|Heavyweight]]\n|{{n/a|Bye}}\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[Juan Nogueira|Nogueira]]|BRA|2016 Summer}}<br />'''W''' 3\u20130\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[Clemente Russo|Russo]]|ITA|2016 Summer}}<br />'''W''' 3\u20130\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[Rustam Tulaganov|Tulaganov]]|UZB|2016 Summer}}<br />'''W''' 3\u20130\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[Vasiliy Levit|Levit]]|KAZ|2016 Summer}}<br />'''W''' 3\u20130\n|{{gold01}}\n|}\n\n;Women\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:90%\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Athlete\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Event\n!Round of 16\n!Quarterfinals\n!Semifinals\n!colspan=2|Final\n|-style=\"font-size:95%\"\n!Opposition<br />Result\n!Opposition<br />Result\n!Opposition<br />Result\n!Opposition<br />Result\n!Rank\n|-align=center\n|align=left|'''[[Anastasia Belyakova]]'''\n|align=left|[[Boxing at the 2016 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's lightweight|Lightweight]]\n|{{n/a|Bye}}\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[Mikaela Mayer|Mayer]]|USA|2016 Summer}}<br />'''W''' 2\u20130\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[Estelle Mossely|Mossely]]|FRA|2016 Summer}}<br />'''L''' {{abbr|TKO|Technical Knockout}}\n|Did not advance\n|{{bronze03}}\n|-align=center\n|align=left|[[Yaroslava Yakushina]]\n|align=left|[[Boxing at the 2016 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's middleweight|Middleweight]]\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[Chen Nien-chin|Chen N-c]]|TPE|2016 Summer}}<br />'''W''' 3\u20130\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[Claressa Shields|Shields]]|USA|2016 Summer}}<br />'''L''' 0\u20133\n|colspan=3|Did not advance\n|}\n\n==Canoeing==\n{{main article|Canoeing at the 2016 Summer Olympics}}\n\n===Slalom===\nRussian canoeists have qualified a maximum of one boat in each of the following classes through the [[2015 ICF Canoe Slalom World Championships]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Slalom Powerhouses Comfortably Qualify for Rio|url=http://www.canoeicf.com/news/slalom-powerhouses-comfortably-qualify-rio|publisher=[[International Canoe Federation]]|date=12 October 2015|accessdate=16 October 2015}}</ref> The slalom canoeing team, including four returning Olympians from London 2012, was selected to the Russian roster at the [[2016 European Canoe Slalom Championships|2016 European Championships]] on 15 May 2016.<ref>{{cite news|script-title=ru:\u041d\u0430\u0437\u0432\u0430\u043d \u0441\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0430\u0432 \u0441\u0431\u043e\u0440\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0438 \u043f\u043e \u0433\u0440\u0435\u0431\u043d\u043e\u043c\u0443 \u0441\u043b\u0430\u043b\u043e\u043c\u0443 \u043d\u0430 \u041e\u043b\u0438\u043c\u043f\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0435 \u0438\u0433\u0440\u044b-2016|trans-title=Slalom canoeists were named to the Russian national team for the 2016 Olympics|language=ru|url=http://www.championat.com/other/news-2464532-nazvan-sostav-sbornoj-rossii-po-grebnomu-slalomu-na-olimpijskie-igry-2016.html|accessdate=17 May 2016|publisher=Championat.com|date=15 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:90%\"\n|-\n!rowspan=2|Athlete\n!rowspan=2|Event\n!colspan=6|Preliminary\n!colspan=2|Semifinal\n!colspan=2|Final\n|- style=\"font-size:95%\"\n!Run 1\n!Rank\n!Run 2\n!Rank\n!Best\n!Rank\n!Time\n!Rank\n!Time\n!Rank\n|- align=center\n|align=left|[[Alexander Lipatov]]\n|align=left|[[Canoeing at the 2016 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's slalom C-1|Men's C-1]]\n|101.78\n|10\n|98.72\n|7\n|98.72\n|10 '''Q'''\n|104.69\n|13\n|colspan=2|Did not advance\n|- align=center\n|align=left|[[Mikhail Kuznetsov (canoeist)|Mikhail Kuznetsov]]<br />[[Dmitry Larionov]]\n|align=left|[[Canoeing at the 2016 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's slalom C-2|Men's C-2]]\n| 167.26\n| 12\n|107.39\n|5\n|107.39\n|8 '''Q'''\n|112.39 \n|8 '''Q'''\n|106.70\n|6\n|- align=center\n|align=left|[[Pavel Eigel]]\n|align=left|[[Canoeing at the 2016 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's slalom K-1|Men's K-1]]\n|96.72\n|15\n|88.57\n|4\n|88.57\n|6 '''Q'''\n|92.43\n|7 '''Q'''\n|92.62\n|9\n|- align=center\n|align=left|[[Marta Kharitonova]]\n|align=left|[[Canoeing at the 2016 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's slalom K-1|Women's K-1]]\n|111.01\n|13\n|104.72\n|5\n|104.72\n|8 '''Q'''\n|160.39\n|15\n|colspan=2|Did not advance\n|}\n\n===Sprint===\nRussian canoeists have qualified a total of ten boats in each of the following distances for the Games through the [[2015 ICF Canoe Sprint World Championships]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Olympic Canoe Sprint Qualification spots confirmed|url=http://www.canoeicf.com/news/olympic-canoe-sprint-qualification-spots-confirmed|publisher=[[International Canoe Federation]]|date=6 September 2015|accessdate=8 September 2015}}</ref> Meanwhile, one additional boat was awarded to the Russian squad in men's K-1 1000 m by virtue of a top two national finish at the 2016 European Qualification Regatta in [[Duisburg]], [[Germany]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Euro Olympic quotas secured|url=http://www.canoeicf.com/news/euro-olympic-quotas-secured|publisher=[[International Canoe Federation]]|date=19 May 2016|accessdate=20 May 2016}}</ref> \nAs a response to the \"multiple positive cases\" of doping by Belarus and Romania, two further spare boats were accepted by the Russian team to round out the roster size to ten.\n\nA total of 14 sprint canoeists (11 men and 3 women) were named to the Russian roster for the Games on 15 July 2016, with [[Alexander Dyachenko]] and [[Yury Postrigay]] looking to defend their men's sprint kayak double title at the Rio regatta.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://tass.ru/sport/3457159|script-title=ru:\u041d\u0430\u0437\u0432\u0430\u043d \u0441\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0430\u0432 \u0441\u0431\u043e\u0440\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0438 \u043f\u043e \u0433\u0440\u0435\u0431\u043b\u0435 \u043d\u0430 \u0431\u0430\u0439\u0434\u0430\u0440\u043a\u0430\u0445 \u0438 \u043a\u0430\u043d\u043e\u044d \u043d\u0430 \u041e\u0418-2016|trans-title=Russia names the flatware canoeing team for the Olympics|language=ru|publisher=[[Russian News Agency TASS]]|date=15 July 2016|accessdate=16 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn 26 July 2016, the [[International Canoe Federation]] announced that five selected Russian sprint canoeists, namely Yelena Anyushina, [[Natalia Podolskaya]], [[Alexander Dyachenko]], [[Andrey Kraitor]] and [[Aleksey Korovashkov]], had been implicated in the DPM benefiting from the state-sponsored doping program. As a result, the Russian entries in the men's C-1 200 m, men's C-2 1000 m, and men's K-2 200 m, along with the women's events (K-1 200 m, K-1 500 m, and K-2 500 m), were removed, with four of the quota places being provisionally re-allocated to the different NOCs \u2013 women's K-2 500 m to [[Austria at the 2016 Summer Olympics|Austria]], women's K-1 200 m to [[Germany at the 2016 Summer Olympics|Germany]], men's K-2 200 m to [[Sweden at the 2016 Summer Olympics|Sweden]] and men's C-1 200 m to [[Iran at the 2016 Summer Olympics|Iran]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.canoeicf.com/news/canoeing-removes-five-russian-athletes-rio-2016-olympic-games|title=Canoeing Removes Five Russian Athletes from Rio 2016 Olympic Games|publisher=[[International Canoe Federation]]|accessdate=26 July 2016}}</ref> Kraitor's decision was reconsidered and was allowed to compete a day before the opening of the Games.<ref name=\":9\" />\n\n;Men\n{|class=wikitable style=\"font-size:90%\"\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Athlete\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Event\n!colspan=2|Heats\n!colspan=2|Semifinals\n!colspan=2|Final\n|-style=\"font-size:95%\"\n!Time\n!Rank\n!Time\n!Rank\n!Time\n!Rank\n|-align=center\n|align=left|'''[[Roman Anoshkin]]'''\n|align=left|[[Canoeing at the 2016 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's K-1 1000 metres|K-1 1000 m]]\n|3:37.296\n|5 '''Q'''\n|3:34.833\n|1 '''FA'''\n|3:33.363\n|{{bronze03}}\n|-align=center\n|align=left|[[Andrey Kraitor]]\n|align=left|[[Canoeing at the 2016 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's C-1 200 metres|\u0421-1 200 m]]\n|39.985\n|1 '''Q'''\n|40.394\n|1 '''FA'''\n|40.105\n|6\n|-align=center\n|align=left|[[Evgenii Lukantsov]]\n|align=left|[[Canoeing at the 2016 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's K-1 200 metres|K-1 200 m]]\n|35.245\n|4 '''Q'''\n|35.567\n|7 '''FB'''\n|37.482\n|14\n|-align=center\n|align=left|[[Ilya Shtokalov]]\n|align=left|[[Canoeing at the 2016 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's C-1 1000 metres|C-1 1000 m]]\n|4:02.626\n|3 '''Q'''\n|3:58.259\n|1 '''FA'''\n|4:00.963\n|{{bronze03}}\n|-align=center\n|align=left|[[Ilya Shtokalov]]<br />[[Ilya Pervukhin]]\n|align=left|[[Canoeing at the 2016 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's C-2 1000 metres|C-2 1000 m]]\n|3:43.105\n|3 '''Q'''\n|3:42.127\n|3 '''FA'''\n|3:46.776\n|5\n|-align=center\n|align=left|[[Roman Anoshkin]]<br />[[Kirill Lyapunov]]<br />[[Vasily Pogreban]]<br />[[Oleg Zhestkov]]\n|align=left|[[Canoeing at the 2016 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's K-4 1000 metres|K-4 1000 m]]\n| 2:56.662\n|4 '''Q'''\n|3:01.065\n|4 '''FB'''\n|3:06.825\n|9\n|}\n\n;Women\n{|class=wikitable style=\"font-size:90%\"\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Athlete\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Event\n!colspan=2|Heats\n!colspan=2|Semifinals\n!colspan=2|Final\n|-style=\"font-size:95%\"\n!Time\n!Rank\n!Time\n!Rank\n!Time\n!Rank\n|-align=center\n|align=left|[[Elena Anyushina]] \n|align=left|[[Canoeing at the 2016 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's K-1 500 metres|K-1 500 m]]\n|1:52.597\n|3 '''Q'''\n|1:57.229\n|4 '''FB'''\n|1:57.202\n|9\n|-align=center\n|align=left|[[Elena Anyushina]]<br/>[[Kira Stepanova]]\n|align=left|[[Canoeing at the 2016 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's K-2 500 metres|K-2 500 m]]\n|1:45.906\n|5 '''Q'''\n|1:42.439\n|2 '''FA'''\n|1:46.319\n|5\n|}\n<small>Qualification Legend: '''FA''' = Qualify to final (medal); '''FB''' = Qualify to final B (non-medal)</small>\n\n==Cycling==\n{{main article|Cycling at the 2016 Summer Olympics}}\n\n===Road===\nRussian riders qualified for the following quota places in the men's and women's Olympic road race by virtue of their top 15 final national ranking in the [[2015 UCI Europe Tour]] (for men) and top 22 in the 2016 UCI World Ranking (for women).<ref>{{cite news|title=UCI announces men's road Olympic quotas|url=http://www.cyclingnews.com/news/uci-announces-mens-road-olympic-quotas/|publisher=[[Cyclingnews.com]]|date=18 January 2016|accessdate=20 January 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=UCI announce women's road cycling quotas for Rio Olympics|url=http://www.cyclingnews.com/news/uci-announce-womens-road-cycling-quotas-for-rio-olympics/|publisher=[[Cyclingnews.com]]|date=1 June 2016|accessdate=2 June 2016}}</ref> The road cycling team, highlighted by two-time bronze medalist [[Olga Zabelinskaya]] from London 2012, was named to the Olympic roster on 26 June 2016.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://tass.ru/sport/3403447|script-title=ru:\u0412\u0435\u043b\u043e\u0433\u043e\u043d\u0449\u0438\u043a\u0438 \u0418\u043b\u044c\u043d\u0443\u0440 \u0417\u0430\u043a\u0430\u0440\u0438\u043d, \u041f\u0430\u0432\u0435\u043b \u041a\u043e\u0447\u0435\u0442\u043a\u043e\u0432 \u0438 \u0421\u0435\u0440\u0433\u0435\u0439 \u0427\u0435\u0440\u043d\u0435\u0446\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0432\u044b\u0441\u0442\u0443\u043f\u044f\u0442 \u043d\u0430 \u041e\u0418-2016|trans-title=Cyclists Ilnur Zakarin, Pavel Kochetkov, and Sergey Chernetskiy will compete in Rio 2016|language=ru|publisher=[[Russian News Agency TASS]]|date=26 June 2016|accessdate=28 June 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn 26 July 2016, [[Union Cycliste Internationale|UCI]] announced that three cyclists with previous bans had been withdrawn by ROC, these including [[Ilnur Zakarin]], [[Olga Zabelinskaya]] and track rider [[Sergei Shilov]]. A further three unnamed riders were implicated in the 'disappearing positive methodology' uncovered by Richard McLaren's report into state-sanctioned doping.<ref>{{cite news|title=UCI confirms three Russian cyclists withdrawn from Olympic Games|url=http://www.cyclingnews.com/news/uci-confirms-three-russian-cyclists-withdrawn-from-olympic-games//|publisher=[[Cyclingnews.com]]|date=28 July 2016|accessdate=28 July 2016}}</ref><ref name=cycling-doping>{{cite news|url=http://www.sports.ru/others/cycle-racing/1042461781.html|script-title=ru:\u0421\u0432\u0435\u0448\u043d\u0438\u043a\u043e\u0432 \u0438 \u0421\u043e\u043a\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0432 \u043d\u0435 \u0434\u043e\u043f\u0443\u0449\u0435\u043d\u044b \u0434\u043e \u0420\u0438\u043e-2016, \u0442\u0430\u043a \u043a\u0430\u043a \u0431\u044b\u043b\u0438 \u0443\u043f\u043e\u043c\u044f\u043d\u0443\u0442\u044b \u0432 \u0434\u043e\u043a\u043b\u0430\u0434\u0435 \u041c\u0430\u043a\u043b\u0430\u0440\u0435\u043d\u0430|trans-title=Sveshnikov and Sokolov banned from rio 2016, as mentioned in the McLaren report|language=ru|publisher=Sports.ru|date=29 July 2016|accessdate=30 July 2016}}</ref> On 5 August 2016, the date of the Opening Ceremony, Zabelinskaya's, Shilov's and Zakarin's bans were reversed and they were cleared to compete.<ref name=\":13\"/>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:90%\"\n|-\n!Athlete\n!Event\n!Time\n!Rank\n|-align=center\n|align=left|[[Sergey Chernetskiy]]\n|align=left |[[Cycling at the 2016 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's individual road race|Men's road race]]\n|6:19:43 \t\n|31\n|-align=center\n|align=left rowspan=2|[[Pavel Kochetkov]]\n|align=left |[[Cycling at the 2016 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's individual road race|Men's road race]]\n|6:22:23 \t\n|38\n|-align=center\n|align=left|[[Cycling at the 2016 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's road time trial|Men's time trial]]\n| 1:20:07.59\n|28\n|-align=center\n|align=left|[[Alexey Kurbatov]]\n|align=left |[[Cycling at the 2016 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's individual road race|Men's road race]]\n|colspan=2|Did not finish\n|-align=center\n|align=left rowspan=2|'''[[Olga Zabelinskaya]]'''\n|align=left|[[Cycling at the 2016 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's individual road race|Women's road race]]\n|3:55:52 \t\n|16\n|-align=center\n|align=left|[[Cycling at the 2016 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's road time trial|Women's time trial]]\n|44:31.97\n|{{silver02}}\n|}\n\n===Track===\nFollowing the completion of the [[2016 UCI Track Cycling World Championships]], Russian riders have accumulated spots in the men's team pursuit and women's team sprint. As a result of their place in the women's team sprint, Russia has assured its right to enter two riders in the women's sprint and keirin. Although Russia failed to earn a place in the men's team sprint, they managed to secure a single berth in the men's keirin and two more in the men's sprint, by virtue of their final individual UCI Olympic rankings in those events.\n\nOn 26 July 2016, [[Union Cycliste Internationale|UCI]] announced that three cyclists with previous bans had been withdrawn by ROC, these including track rider [[Sergei Shilov]]. A further three unnamed riders were implicated in the 'disappearing positive methodology' uncovered by Richard McLaren's report into state-sanctioned doping. The UCI confirmed that the men's pursuit team from which Shilov was excluded would be allowed to replace him only from the existing pool of accepted athletes. The following day, two further track cyclists, [[Kirill Sveshnikov]] and [[Dmitri Sokolov (cyclist)|Dmitri Sokolov]] were named as implicated in the methodology, and withdrawn, placing the Russian entry in the men's team pursuit in doubt.<ref name=cycling-doping/><ref>{{cite news|title=UCI confirms three Russian cyclists withdrawn from Olympic Games|url=http://www.cyclingnews.com/news/uci-confirms-three-russian-cyclists-withdrawn-from-olympic-games/|publisher=[[Cyclingnews.com]]|date=28 July 2016|accessdate=28 July 2016}}</ref>\n\n;Sprint\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:90%\"\n!rowspan=2|Athlete\n!rowspan=2|Event\n!colspan=2|Qualification\n!Round 1\n!Repechage 1\n!Round 2\n!Repechage 2\n!Quarterfinals\n!Semifinals\n!colspan=2|Final\n|-style=\"font-size:95%\"\n!Time<br />Speed (km/h)\n!Rank\n!Opposition<br />Time<br />Speed (km/h)\n!Opposition<br />Time<br />Speed (km/h)\n!Opposition<br />Time<br />Speed (km/h)\n!Opposition<br />Time<br />Speed (km/h)\n!Opposition<br />Time<br />Speed (km/h)\n!Opposition<br />Time<br />Speed (km/h)\n!Opposition<br />Time<br />Speed (km/h)\n!Rank\n|-align=center\n|align=left|'''[[Denis Dmitriev]]'''\n|align=left rowspan=2|[[Cycling at the 2016 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's sprint|Men's sprint]]\n|9.774<br />73.664\n|4 '''Q'''\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[Rafa\u0142 Sarnecki|Sarnecki]]|POL|2016 Summer}}<br/>'''W''' 10.141<br />70.998\n|{{n/a|Bye}}\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[Sam Webster (cyclist)|Webster]]|NZL|2016 Summer}}<br/>'''W''' 10.102<br />71.273\n|{{n/a|Bye}}\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[Gr\u00e9gory Baug\u00e9|Baug\u00e9]]|FRA|2016 Summer}}<br/>'''W''' 10.202, '''W''' 10.166\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[Jason Kenny|Kenny]]|GBR|2016 Summer}}<br/>'''W''' 10.139, '''L''', '''L'''\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[Matthew Glaetzer|Glaetzer]]|AUS|2016 Summer}}<br />'''W'''  10.105, '''W'''  10.190\n|{{bronze03}}\n|-align=center\n|align=left|[[Nikita Shurshin]]\n|10.418<br />69.111\n|26\n|colspan=8|Did not advance\n|-align=center\n|align=left|[[Daria Shmeleva]]\n|align=left rowspan=2|[[Cycling at the 2016 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's sprint|Women's sprint]]\n|11.230<br/>64.113\n|22\n|colspan=9|Did not advance\n|-align=center\n|align=left|[[Anastasia Voynova]]\n|10.985<br/>65.543\n|11 '''Q'''\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[Stephanie Morton|Morton]]|AUS|2016 Summer}}<br />'''W''' 11.503<br/>62.592\n| {{n/a|Bye}}\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[Zhong Tianshi|Zhong Ts]]|CHN|2016 Summer}}<br />'''W''' 11.271<br/>63.880\n|{{n/a|Bye}}\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[Elis Ligtlee|Ligtlee]]|NED|2016 Summer}}<br />'''L''',  '''L'''\n|Did not advance\n|''5th place final''<br />{{flagIOCathlete|[[Zhong Tianshi|Zhong]]|CHN|2016 Summer}}<br />{{flagIOCathlete|[[Lee Wai Sze|Lee W S]]|HKG|2016 Summer}}<br />{{flagIOCathlete|[[Simona Krupeckait\u0117|Krupeckait\u0117]]|LTU|2016 Summer}}<br />'''L'''\n|8\n|}\n\n;Team sprint\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:90%\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Athlete\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Event\n!colspan=2|Qualification\n!colspan=2|Semifinals\n!colspan=2|Final\n|-style=\"font-size:95%\"\n!Time<br />Speed (km/h)\n!Rank\n!Opposition<br />Time<br />Speed (km/h)\n!Rank\n!Opposition<br />Time<br />Speed (km/h)\n!Rank\n|-align=center\n|align=left|'''[[Daria Shmeleva]]<br />[[Anastasia Voynova]]'''\n|align=left|[[Cycling at the 2016 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's team sprint|Women's team sprint]]\n|32.655<br />55.121\n|2 '''Q'''\n|{{flagIOCteam|CAN|2016 Summer}}<br/>'''W''' 32.324<br />55.686\n|2 '''Q'''\n|{{flagIOCteam|CHN|2016 Summer}}<br/>'''L''' 32.401<br />55.553\n|{{silver02}}\n|}\n\n;Keirin\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:90%\"\n!rowspan=2|Athlete\n!rowspan=2|Event\n!1st Round\n!Repechage\n!2nd Round\n!Final\n|-style=\"font-size:95%\"\n!Rank\n!Rank\n!Rank\n!Rank\n|-align=center\n|align=left|[[Denis Dmitriev]]\n|align=left|[[Cycling at the 2016 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's Keirin|Men's keirin]]\n|4 '''R'''\n|2\n|colspan=2| Did not advance\n|-align=center\n|align=left|[[Daria Shmeleva]]\n|align=left rowspan=2|[[Cycling at the 2016 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's Keirin|Women's keirin]]\n|3 '''R'''\n|2 \n|colspan=2| Did not advance\n|-align=center\n|align=left|[[Anastasia Voynova]]\n|4 '''R'''\n|1 '''Q'''\n|3 '''Q'''\n|4\n|}\n\n===Mountain biking===\nRussia has qualified one mountain biker for the women's Olympic cross-country race, as a result of her nation's ninth-place finish in the UCI Olympic Ranking List of 25 May 2016. Due to the lack of eligible NOCs for Oceania on the list, the unused berth was added to the Russian mountain biking team as the next highest-ranked nation, not yet qualified, in the men's cross-country race. Beijing 2008 bronze medalist [[Irina Kalentieva]] and rookie Anton Sintsov were named to Russia's mountain biking team for the Games on 3 July 2016.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://ria.ru/sport/20160703/1457494070.html|script-title=ru:\u041c\u0430\u0443\u043d\u0442\u0438\u043d\u0431\u0430\u0439\u043a\u0435\u0440\u044b \u041a\u0430\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0442\u044c\u0435\u0432\u0430, \u0418\u0432\u0430\u043d\u043e\u0432 \u0438 \u0421\u0438\u043d\u0446\u043e\u0432 \u0431\u0443\u0434\u0443\u0442 \u0437\u0430\u044f\u0432\u043b\u0435\u043d\u044b \u043d\u0430 \u041e\u0418 \u043e\u0442 \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0438|trans-title=Mountain bikers Kalentieva, Ivanov, and Sintsov will compete for Russia at the Olympics|language=ru|publisher=[[RIA Novosti]]|date=3 July 2016|accessdate=6 July 2016}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:90%\"\n|-\n!Athlete\n!Event\n!Time\n!Rank\n|-align=center\n|align=left|[[Anton Sintsov]]\n|align=left|[[Cycling at the 2016 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's cross-country|Men's cross-country]]\n|1:37:38\n|12\n|-align=center\n|align=left|[[Irina Kalentieva]]\n|align=left|[[Cycling at the 2016 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's cross-country|Women's cross-country]]\n|1:36:54\n|17\n|}\n\n===BMX===\nRussian riders qualified for one men's and one women's quota place for BMX at the Olympics, as a result of the nation's seventh-place finish for women in the UCI Olympic Ranking List and top four for men in the UCI BMX Individual Ranking List of 31 May 2016. The BMX riders were named to the Olympic roster on 3 June 2016.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://rsport.ru/cycling/20160603/929890973.html|script-title=ru:\u0421\u0431\u043e\u0440\u043d\u0443\u044e \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0438 \u043f\u043e \u0412\u041c\u0425 \u043d\u0430 \u041e\u0418-2016 \u043f\u0440\u0435\u0434\u0441\u0442\u0430\u0432\u044f\u0442 \u042f\u0440\u043e\u0441\u043b\u0430\u0432\u0430 \u0411\u043e\u043d\u0434\u0430\u0440\u0435\u043d\u043a\u043e \u0438 \u0415\u0432\u0433\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0439 \u041a\u043e\u043c\u0430\u0440\u043e\u0432|trans-title=Yaroslava Bondarenko and Evgeny Komarov will represent the Russian team in BMX at the 2016 Olympics|language=ru|publisher=[[Rossiya Segodnya]]|date=3 June 2016|accessdate=5 June 2016}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:90%;\"\n|-\n!rowsp